 medical, scientific, linguistic, religious and material meanings. Ten scholars from the fields of culinary history, history of medicine and science, divinity, archaeology and material culture, and English literature and linguistics contribute to a vibrant mapping of the aspirations invested in, and uses of, recipes and recipe books. By exploring areas as various as the knowledge economies of medicine, Anglican feasting and fasting practices, the material culture of the kitchen and table, London publishing and concepts of authorship and the aesthetics of culinary styles, these eleven essays (including a critical introduction to recipe books and their historiography) position recipe texts in the wider culture of the sixteenth, seventeenth and eighteenth centuries. They illuminate their importance to both their original compilers and users, and modern scholars and graduate students alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCookbooks. 0aFood writers. 0aFood writing. 0aMedicinexHistoryy17th century. 0aMedicinexHistoryy18th century. 4aLiterature Studies 2020. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aBoscawen family.  aEnglish recipes.  aFoote sisters.  aThe Compleat Housewife.  aThe Ladies Directory.  aThe Queen-Like Closet.  aarchaeologists.  aauthorship.  acelebrity.  aculinary recipes.  adomestic life.  aearly modern recipe text.  agenre conventions.  ahousewifery.  amedicinal advice.  amedicinal recipe.  arecipe books.  arecipe manuscripts.1 aAlonso-Almeida, Francisco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArcher, Jayne Elisabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiMeo, Michelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiMeo, Michelle, eedito